<h2 id="makefile">Makefile</h2>
<p>I add a Makefile to every project I work with. I don&rsquo;t usually work on C/C++ projects or any other compiled languages but Makefile is good to make aliases for long commands.</p>
<p>Here is an example of short version of Makefile I use:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-makefile" data-lang="makefile"><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#a6e22e">.PHONY</span><span style="color:#f92672">:</span> up
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#a6e22e">up</span><span style="color:#f92672">:</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>	docker-compose up -d
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#a6e22e">.PHONY</span><span style="color:#f92672">:</span> logs
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#a6e22e">logs</span><span style="color:#f92672">:</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>	tail -f ./storage/logs/*.log
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>There are set of aliases / mnemonics that I used to:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>make up</code> - start the project. May be docker-compose or set of commands to turn the project into &ldquo;running&rdquo; state</li>
<li><code>make down</code> - stop everything <code>make up</code> did</li>
<li><code>make tags</code> - generate tags</li>
<li><code>make logs</code> - watch logs where ever they are</li>
</ul>
<p>Since I work with multiple languages and frameworks, thanks to this approach, I don&rsquo;t need to remember how to start a project, how to compile JS files, how to read logs, etc&hellip; All those commands are hidden under <code>make</code> targets.</p>
<p>On the other hand Makefiles aren&rsquo;t designed for such use. <code>make</code> is super powerful tool and using it as an alias system just feels wrong.</p>
<h2 id="taskfile">Taskfile</h2>
<p>Taskfile - is just a shell script where you can define functions to call.</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#66d9ef">function</span> up <span style="color:#f92672">{</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> podman-compose up -d --build
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#f92672">}</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#66d9ef">function</span> down <span style="color:#f92672">{</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> podman-compose down
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#f92672">}</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#66d9ef">function</span> npm <span style="color:#f92672">{</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> podman run -it -v <span style="color:#e6db74">`</span>pwd<span style="color:#e6db74">`</span>:/app -w /app node:latest npm $@
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#f92672">}</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#66d9ef">function</span> composer <span style="color:#f92672">{</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> podman-compose exec app composer $@
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span><span style="color:#f92672">}</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>TIMEFORMAT<span style="color:#f92672">=</span><span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;Task completed in %3lR&#34;</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>time <span style="color:#e6db74">${</span>@<span style="color:#66d9ef">:-</span>default<span style="color:#e6db74">}</span>
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Place this file in your project root, make it executable and you can call those aliases with <code>./Taskfile up</code> or <code>./Taskfile composer install</code>.</p>
<p>To simplify this a bit add this line to you bashrc/zshrc:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span style="display:flex;"><span>alias run<span style="color:#f92672">=</span>./Taskfile
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Now you can call all those commands as <code>run up</code> or <code>run composer install</code>.
Pretty handy.</p>
<p>This idea was borrowed from <a href="https://github.com/adriancooney">Adrian Cooney</a> and his <a href="https://github.com/adriancooney/Taskfile">Taskfile repo</a>.</p>